Paul,

Currently using the Cantera Reactor class this is hard to do.  It 
allows you to fix T, or solve the energy equation, but it doesn&#39;t allow 
specified T(time), or P(time).

For now, probably the best thing to do is to write the ODEs yourself, 
and use Cantera to evaluate the terms in the equations. See, for 
example, the Cantera MATLAB demos &quot;ignite.m&quot;, &quot;ignite2.m&quot;, and the 
function in the Cantera toolbox &quot;reactor_ode.m&quot; for an example of this 
approach. The MATLAB stiff ODE integrator used in these demos works 
fine for these problems.

I have actually written a new class &quot;FlowReactor&quot; that is closer to 
what you want, but it is not ready for release yet.   It is designed to 
simulate reacting plug flow in a channel, and includes compressibility 
effects, heat loss, friction, etc.  I&#39;ll make sure to allow specified 
T(x) and P(x) as an option.  I don&#39;t know precisely when this will be 
ready for release - maybe in a couple of weeks.

Dave


